>>Hadi: Feature Stories, which is Heading 2.It automatically conveys the informationthat this section is a subsection of the 

84
00:05:51,733 --> 00:05:54,966
heading above.

85
00:05:54,966 --> 00:05:58,966
You know you will see also that overall get an outline

86
00:05:58,966 --> 00:06:03,566
of the page and the major sections of that.

87
00:06:03,566 --> 00:06:08,066
That is the difference between accessible and inaccessible.

88
00:06:08,066 --> 00:06:12,366
>>Sheryl: That screen reader can only access the text that's presented on the screen

89
00:06:12,366 --> 00:06:17,332
and so if someone just scans in a document and puts an image up on their website

90
00:06:17,333 --> 00:06:20,366
that screen reader is not going to be able to read that content.

91
00:06:20,366 --> 00:06:25,699
And so the web developer in that case needs to know to create all their materials

92
00:06:25,700 --> 00:06:28,600
so that they're accessible to a screen reader, in other words

93
00:06:28,600 --> 00:06:34,366
so they can access the text for that screen reader to read it aloud

94
00:06:34,366 --> 00:06:36,366
to a person who's blind.

95
00:06:36,366 --> 00:06:38,899
>>Screen reader: Enter.Message from.Hi All.

96
00:06:38,900 --> 00:06:40,733
>>Sheryl: It’s essential that people with disabilities

97
00:06:40,733 --> 00:06:45,033
have access to assistive technology but that’s not the end of the story.

98
00:06:45,033 --> 00:06:48,333
In order for them to be effective users of technology,

99
00:06:48,333 --> 00:06:55,333
the technology that other people developlike websites and software and PDF files and so forth

100
00:06:55,333 --> 00:07:01,666
must be designed in such a waythat they can use it with their assistive technology.

101
